text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LanguageOfTheNacirema]]%0a%0a!Philosophy Lessons from LIKE%0a%0a:Author: david_h%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aAnalyzing the polysemy of the word LIKE in Nacirema culture%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aIn a world with billions of people, there is LIKEly to be another person LIKE you. Not exactly the same, but somewhat aLIKE. You make have LIKE interests or LIKE the same food, but, LIKE, not really be the same person. It is much easier now to meet these people, especially with social media and the LIKE. Websites and apps LIKE Facebook, Twitter, or Instagram are good examples. It's nice to see LIKE-minded individuals. Perhaps when you meet them you ought to send them a LIKE. Or maybe you are LIKE "I'm too shy." Well, no problem. Maybe we aren't so unLIKE, because I also disLIKE the visibility of social media.%0a%0aThe concept of "like" has been around in the Nacirema for generations. First learned from daily speech with family and further solidified in more formal learning settings. In its most basic form, the concept centers on the quality of similarity. This is unsurprising; as with many cultures, many objects and ideas accepted in Nacirema culture were first learned by describing their relative significance to the Nacirema people as well as their affinity towards something. In the past few decades, though the concept already existed prior, there has greater emphasis on "like" as a noun and a verb as a form of affirmation. Coupled with the rise of individualism, younger Naciremans see a greater need to affirm their importance in the booming Nacirema society.%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210327-201252-471400#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Alternative Interpretation of LIKE %0a-> - JoshuaC%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aThe Nacireman word “LIKE” is used to represent two different concepts – similarity as well as enjoyment or appreciation. This suggests that there is some inherent link between these two concepts in Nacireman culture. One possible interpretation is the Nacirema people only enjoy or “like” people who share certain similarities to them. Another broader interpretation is that the Nacirema people only enjoy objects or concepts that are similar to what they’ve seen in the past (ie that they’re familiar with). Overall, the polysemy of the word “LIKE” suggests that the Nacirema, in general, avoid outsiders as well as unfamiliar concepts or objects. It might be that they are not open to new people or new experiences. It might even be risky to approach or interact with them.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210327-201252-471400#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: E:)%0a(:Category: LanguageOfTheNacirema:)
